105—14. The connexion of ideas is very obscure. Man has affinity with the divine mundus. Seeing that the animals have this (=post haec, 105), then so a fortiori must man. But, apart from this, nature has given him purpose and speech and intelligence and a swiftness of spirit, which shows the presence in him of God. Man seeks God: buthe can only do so because God guides his seeking. God seeks himself (se ipse requirit) in man’s seeking of him (106—8). That it is God that guides man’s seekings we may see pre-eminently (putting aside other indications—mitlo . . . mitto—omitting what is noted in 109-14) from the study of astronomy (115-16) ; sor who could hope to find the mundus nisi qui pars ipse deorum est? In 109-14 proofs that man’s search is directed by God are found in certain arts other than astronomy (alias 109), yet these, though permitted to man, are uncertain (ῑφψιίας) and not wholly within human competence (110); therefore Manilius will not press them into the service of his argument (mztto). Moreover, nothing in any department of human inquiry has been granted to us aequalz sub leoe— all clear and in order (111) 3 our authorities are not men of the highest talents (112)· , how then could we hope lo find God unless God guz‘ded us? In the above analysis Ι have italicized those amplifications of Manilius' argument which it seemed to me necessary to make in order to bring out the connexion of ideas. But I am bound to say that the more I reflect on this passage the more obscure I find it.
